post_text:
CONGRATULATIONS to Clare Kuntz 🎉🎉🎉

KSHAA Citizenship Award: 🏅

Given each year to one Graduating 8th Grade Male and Female student.

This award honors young people who demonstrate;

"Respect" for fellow students, staff, the school, and their community at all times.

"Responsibility" with academics, school activities, sports, and the culture /pride at their school.

"Reverence" by showing kindness, care, and compassion for everyone.

"Leadership" is demonstrated in everything they do at school, on the playing field, and in their community.

Clare is an exceptional young lady who works hard and strives to be the best person she can be every day.. She is kind hearted and helpful to others and would do anything for her school and fellow classmates. She is respected by her peers and the school staff. Clare is very deserving of this honor. The staff at CMS is proud of her and wish her continued success at CHS!👏👏👏

The USD 473 Athletic Department is releasing our summer opportunities and steps to ensure safe return to activities during the COVID-19 pandemic. All dates are subject to change based on Federal, State, and Local guidelines.

Attention - Parents and Students:

This is for any student who was unable to pick up their personal belongings from their locker back in March.

Personal belongings may be picked up this Tuesday, May 26th from 2:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m. at the main entrance of the School.

You will pull up to the main entrance of the school and someone will come to your car and get your name. Please stay in your car because we cannot allow anyone in the school building.

Personal belongings not picked up on Tuesday will be stored until August.

Thanks
Ms. Wright

Hello CMS Students!

The first week of Online Learning is in the books. Thank you for working with your teachers and being flexible as we make adjustments to our Zoom schedule for next week to better meet the needs of our students.

Remember, if you have questions or issues, please reach out to your teachers or me. We are here to support you as we continue this new way of learning during these difficult times.

Assignments for the upcoming week should all be posted in your Google Classroom sites now. Be sure to download them and start working on them as you have time so you will be ready for next week's Zoom sessions.

Keep up the good work students!!!

Irish Proud
Ms. Wright

Please be patient next week. This is new to all of us and we may experience some glitches. We will all have to be flexible and work together as a team.

If you have any questions, concerns, or needs....please reach out to me via email at mwright@usd473.net. I am here to support you and your child.

Thanks

post_text:
Dickinson County Game Warden Lance Hockett is shown talking to Mr. Fewin’s KDWPT Hunter Safety Class at Chapman Middle School.

Mr. Hockett visited about his duties as a Game Warden in the State of KS, as well as showing the students how his K-9 Officer Kodak works.

After his presentation the Student’s were allowed to pet & play with Kodak. Officer Hockett visits Mr. Fewin’s classes 2 and 3 times a year and is always involved in working with Chapman Archery Tournaments.

We greatly appreciate Lance taking time to come to our School & be with our students.

post_text:
Mrs. Stalder’s 6th grade language arts classes just finished the book, Small Steps: The Year I got Polio by Peg Kehret. The memoir is about Peg’s life with polio. As a culminating activity to the book, Mrs. Stalder has Beth Schmitt speak to the students.
Beth contracted polio when she was 13 years old. The students were very attentive and enthralled with Beth’s presentation.
“Learning about the things that Beth went through that were the same and different from Peg, really helped us understand what their lives were like with polio."
"My favorite part was when Beth talked about how her sisters and family all helped her.”
Beth’s message to the students concluded with Beth encouraging the students to never give even when the situation seems dire. The love of family and faith in God can get you through anything.
